 \mathopen {}\left \lparen p : x\approx _{\mathcal {A}} y\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\textstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen p : x\approx _{\mathcal {A}} y\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\scriptstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen p : x\approx _{\mathcal {A}} y\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\scriptscriptstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen p : x\approx _{\mathcal {A}} y\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}} u \approx _{\mathcal {B} x} p^*v.

Let \mathcal {A} be a path object and let \mathcal {B}\colon  
 \mathopen {}\left \lvert \mathcal {A}\right \rvert \mathclose {}
 \to  \mathsf {PathObj} be a family of path objects. A right cleaving of \mathcal {B} over \mathcal {A} is defined by the following data:

fr:ol.fr:li:
a pullback operation assigning to each edge p\colon  x\approx _{\mathcal {A}} y a map p^* \colon  
 \mathopen {}\left \lvert \mathcal {B} y\right \rvert \mathclose {}
 \to  
 \mathopen {}\left \lvert \mathcal {B} x\right \rvert \mathclose {}
;

a family \Phi _{\mathcal {B}} \colon  \mathchoice {\textstyle \prod _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:
 \mathopen {}\left \lvert \mathcal {A}\right \rvert \mathclose {}
,b:
 \mathopen {}\left \lvert \mathcal {B} x\right \rvert \mathclose {}
\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\textstyle \prod _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:
 \mathopen {}\left \lvert \mathcal {A}\right \rvert \mathclose {}
,b:
 \mathopen {}\left \lvert \mathcal {B} x\right \rvert \mathclose {}
\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\scriptstyle \prod _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:
 \mathopen {}\left \lvert \mathcal {A}\right \rvert \mathclose {}
,b:
 \mathopen {}\left \lvert \mathcal {B} x\right \rvert \mathclose {}
\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\scriptscriptstyle \prod _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:
 \mathopen {}\left \lvert \mathcal {A}\right \rvert \mathclose {}
,b:
 \mathopen {}\left \lvert \mathcal {B} x\right \rvert \mathclose {}
\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}} b \approx _{\mathcal {B} x} \mathsf {rx}_{\mathcal {A}}{x}^*b witnessing the unit law that pullback along the reflexivity datum \mathsf {rx}_{\mathcal {A}}{x}\colon  x\approx _{\mathcal {A}} x is the identity function.

fr:mainmatter.fr:p:
A reflexive graph \mathcal {A} is called univalent when for all x:
 \mathopen {}\left \lvert \mathcal {A}\right \rvert \mathclose {}
 the type \mathchoice {\textstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen y:
 \mathopen {}\left \lvert \mathcal {A}\right \rvert \mathclose {}
\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\textstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen y:
 \mathopen {}\left \lvert \mathcal {A}\right \rvert \mathclose {}
\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\scriptstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen y:
 \mathopen {}\left \lvert \mathcal {A}\right \rvert \mathclose {}
\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\scriptscriptstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen y:
 \mathopen {}\left \lvert \mathcal {A}\right \rvert \mathclose {}
\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}} x\approx _{\mathcal {A}} y is a proposition, or (equivalently), is contractible with centre 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x,\mathsf {rx}_{\mathcal {A}}{x}\right \rparen \mathclose {}
. We shall refer to a univalent reflexive graph as a path object.

Let s \colon  B \to  A and r \colon  A \to  B be a pair of maps. A homotopy h \colon  r\circ  s \sim  1_{B} exhibits s as a section of r and r as a retraction of s. Together, 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen s,r\right \rparen \mathclose {}
 are referred to as a section-retraction pair.
